<content type="html">&lt;p&gt;Diary of a Madman (1835; Russian: &#1047;&#1072;&#1087;&#1080;&#1089;&#1082;&#1080; &#1089;&#1091;&#1084;&#1072;&#1089;&#1096;&#1077;&#1076;&#1096;&#1077;&#1075;&#1086;, Zapiski sumasshedshevo) is a farcical short story by Nikolai Gogol. Along with The Overcoat and The Nose, Diary of a Madman is considered to be one of Gogol's greatest short stories. The tale centers on the life of a minor civil servant during the repressive era of Nicholas I. Following the format of a diary, the story shows the descent of the protagonist, Poprishchin, into insanity. Diary of a Madman, the only one of Gogol's works written in first person, follows diary-entry format.&lt;/p&gt;</content>
